response_text:
This is not just a legal question—it is a geopolitical and reputational one.  

Under China’s civil-aviation rules, every non-Chinese carrier that flies to, from or over China must treat Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macau as “parts of China” in its passenger-facing material. The rule is enforced by the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC); failure to comply can trigger a range of sanctions:  

- A public “rectification order” and 30-day deadline to change the web site/app;  
- Suspension of new route, frequency or code-share applications;  
- Refusal of summer/winter season schedule filings;  
- In extreme cases, revocation of the airline’s operating permit to China.  

Those penalties have already been applied to United, Delta, American, Qantas, Air Canada, Zara, Marriott, Medtronic, etc. in 2018-19. All of them ultimately complied.  

1. What “resisting” would look like  
   - Keep “Taiwan” or “Taipei, Taiwan” in the drop-down list and wait for the CAAC notice.  
   - After the notice you can:  
     – Litigate in Chinese courts (no carrier has ever won);  
     – Ask your home government to raise the issue bilaterally (it will be treated as a diplomatic protest and usually ignored);  
     – Take the matter to ICAO (ICAO has no enforcement power over how states regulate ticketing screens).  
   - Meanwhile you will almost certainly lose route approvals and may have to stop selling China-originating tickets through local OTAs and GDSs.  

2. What complying costs you  
   - Apart from the reputational mail you will receive from Taipei and some US/EU politicians, nothing. The wording change is invisible to 99 % of passengers; revenue from Taiwan originates in TWD and is unaffected.  
   - The major cost is internal: you must retest every customer touchpoint (web, mobile, kiosk, airport signage, loyalty programme statements, cargo AWB stock, interline paperwork, joint-venture agreements) and keep them aligned every time you update the site.  

3. What a “middle way” can look like (used by several oneworld and Star carriers)  
   - Use “Taiwan, China” or “Taiwan (China)” in the English site;  
   - Use “中国台湾” on the Chinese-language site;  
   - Retain “Taiwan” alone in the Traditional-Chinese site that is geofenced outside the PRC;  
   - Keep airport code TPE and city name “Taipei” unchanged;  
   - Do not move Taiwan into a separate “domestic” fare category—let the GDS logic treat it as its own country for tariff purposes.  
   This wording satisfies CAAC inspectors while signalling to Taiwan that you are simply following a foreign regulator’s order.  

4. Legal exposure elsewhere  
   - Taiwan’s Ministry of Transportation can fine you for “damaging the national dignity,” but the fine has never been imposed on a foreign carrier and would be unenforceable outside Taiwan.  
   - EU or US sanctions laws do not prohibit you from writing “Taiwan, China,” so there is normally no conflict with home-country regulation.  

Bottom line  
Your legal team is correct that the Chinese requirement is a political claim, but it is imposed as a licensing condition, not a negotiable commercial term. Unless you are willing to walk away from the Chinese market (and overflight rights), the cheapest, lowest-risk course is to make the wording change, keep a paper trail that you did so under regulatory compulsion, and apply the same text across all distribution channels so you cannot be accused of inconsistency.
